description.narrative: (Kenya): The Human Resources for Health Kenya (HRH) mechanism strengthens HRH management systems for better health outcomes. HRH contributes to the Journey to Self-Reliance by implementing the Afya Elimu Fund, a revolving fund that provides low interest tuition fees loans for students in medical training colleges. Beneficiaries then enter gainful employment and contribute towards better health outcomes. As loans get repaid, additional loans are extended to other students. Using FY 2019 funds, this activity builds the capacity of pre-service medical training institutions and Ministry of Health (MOH) in-service training programs. It supports the county HRH management units to ensure a well distributed workforce and strengthen the health worker information system for effective decision-making, and budgeting. Support for county HRH units includes advocacy for increased HRH resources, performance quality, and HRH strategies for attraction, deployment, and retention. Advocacy extends to the MOH and counties to adopt health workforce data systems, which are used to rationalize placement of health workers based on need. To support universal health coverage, community workforce development processes include training of community health extension workers and ensuring community services cadres are recognized so county governments are prepared to adopt and retain them. HRH additionally promotes county forums where workers' unions and county leadership can engage regularly to dialogue on issues and reduce labor disputes. Dialogues between county governments and unions also address the high absenteeism rates and staff turnover, which negatively impact HRH outcomes. Improved linkages with professional associations and continuous medical education institutions ensures health workers have the competence to provide quality health services, hence improving global public health, which supports the Administration's priority of asserting U.S. leadership and influence..
